Yes, you can achieve this by using axios interceptors. Axios interceptors allow you to intercept requests or responses before they are handled by your application. You can set up a response interceptor to check for a status code of 401 and redirect the user back to the home page.

Here is an example of how you can set up a response interceptor in your react application:

```javascript
import axios from 'axios';
import { useHistory } from 'react-router-dom';

axios.interceptors.response.use(response => {
  return response;
}, error => {
  if (error.response.status === 401) {
    const history = useHistory();
    history.push('/');
  }
  return Promise.reject(error);
});
```

In this example, we are setting up a response interceptor that checks for a status code of 401. If the status code is 401, we use the `useHistory` hook from react-router-dom to redirect the user back to the home page.

Make sure to set up the axios interceptors before making any API requests in your application. This way, the interceptor will be able to intercept any responses that return a status code of 401.

Here is a C program that searches through a drive for all files recursively and prints them to the console:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <string.h>
#include <dirent.h>
#include <sys/stat.h>

void search_files(const char *path) {
    DIR *dir;
    struct dirent *entry;
    struct stat statbuf;

    if ((dir = opendir(path)) == NULL) {
        fprintf(stderr, "Cannot open directory %s\n", path);
        return;
    }

    while ((entry = readdir(dir)) != NULL) {
        char full_path[1024];
        snprintf(full_path, sizeof(full_path), "%s/%s", path, entry->d_name);

        if (stat(full_path, &statbuf) == -1) {
            fprintf(stderr, "Cannot get file status %s\n", full_path);
            continue;
        }

        if (S_ISDIR(statbuf.st_mode)) {
            if (strcmp(entry->d_name, ".") == 0 || strcmp(entry->d_name, "..") == 0) {
                continue;
            }
            search_files(full_path);
        } else {
            printf("%s\n", full_path);
        }
    }

    closedir(dir);
}

