To declare an object that can throw an explicit exception in Java, you need to define a method that explicitly declares the exception using the "throws" keyword. Here is an example:

```java
public class MyClass {

    public void myMethod() throws MyException {
        // Some code that may throw MyException
        if(someCondition) {
            throw new MyException("An error occurred");
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            MyClass obj = new MyClass();
            obj.myMethod();
        } catch(MyException e) {
            System.out.println("Caught exception: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}

class MyException extends Exception {
    public MyException(String message) {
        super(message);
    }
}
```

In this example, the `myMethod()` method in the `MyClass` class explicitly declares that it can throw a `MyException` using the `throws` keyword. The `MyException` class extends the `Exception` class to create a custom exception that can be thrown and caught.

When calling `myMethod()` in the `main` method, it is surrounded by a try-catch block to handle the potential exception that may be thrown. If `myMethod()` throws a `MyException`, it will be caught and the error message will be printed.

