To make a graceful shutdown in a Java app on SIGTERM signal, you can use a shutdown hook. A shutdown hook is a thread that is registered with the Java Virtual Machine (JVM) to run when the JVM is shutting down. Here's an example of how you can create a shutdown hook in your Java app:

```java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Runtime.getRuntime().addShutdownHook(new Thread(() -> {
            // Perform cleanup tasks here before shutting down the app
            System.out.println("Shutting down gracefully...");
        }));

        // Your main application code here

        // Keep the main thread running to prevent the app from exiting immediately
        try {
            Thread.sleep(Long.MAX_VALUE);
        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            Thread.currentThread().interrupt();
        }
    }
}
```

In this example, the `addShutdownHook` method registers a new thread that will run when the JVM receives a SIGTERM signal. Inside the thread, you can perform any necessary cleanup tasks before shutting down the app.

When the app receives a SIGTERM signal (e.g., when you use the `kill` command in the terminal), the shutdown hook will be triggered and the "Shutting down gracefully..." message will be printed to the console.

You can customize the shutdown hook to perform any specific cleanup tasks that your app requires before shutting down.

