Yes, you can create a single debounce function that can be used to debounce multiple functions. Here is an example of how you can achieve this:

```javascript
function debounce(func, delay) {
  let timer;

  return function() {
    const context = this;
    const args = arguments;

    clearTimeout(timer);
    timer = setTimeout(() => {
      func.apply(context, args);
    }, delay);
  };
}

// Example debounced functions
function func1() {
  console.log('Function 1 debounced');
}

function func2() {
  console.log('Function 2 debounced');
}

// Create debounced versions of the functions
const debouncedFunc1 = debounce(func1, 500);
const debouncedFunc2 = debounce(func2, 500);

// Call the debounced functions
debouncedFunc1();
debouncedFunc2();
```

In the above example, the `debounce` function takes in a function `func` and a delay `delay` as arguments. It returns a new function that will debounce the original function when called. This allows you to create debounced versions of multiple functions and route them through a single debounce function.

